    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For each distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair, compute aggregated stats over the full available series: count, min, max, mean, median (p50), p90, and p95. Return: (1) a table of these aggregates sorted by count descending, limited to top 50 rows; (2) the full list of distinct cmdb_id values and distinct kpi_name values with their counts. Keep outputs compact (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The prior Executor run aggregated metric.csv by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and returned per-pair statistics (count, min, max, mean, p50, p90, p95) for many component-KPI pairs. The output shows there are 29 distinct cmdb_id values (top by sample count: Mysql02, Mysql01, Redis02, Redis01, Tomcat03) and 347 distinct KPI names. This summary confirms metric data coverage across the possible root-cause components but does not yet localize anomalies within the incident window (2021-03-12 16:00–16:30 UTC+8). To follow the required workflow, we must (1) compute global thresholds (e.g., p95 and p5) for each component-KPI using the full available series (not yet filtered), then (2) filter metric points to the incident time window and detect anomaly points relative to those global thresholds. The next Executor step should produce a compact ranked list of component-KPI pairs that show anomalies inside the given time window (counts and earliest anomaly timestamps), so we can narrow candidate faulty components for further trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv perform the following (keep results stored in kernel variables and return a compact table limited to top 20 rows):\n1) For each distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global p95 and global p5 using the full available series (do NOT filter by time yet).\n2) Filter metric.csv to the incident time window: March 12, 2021 16:00:00 to 2021-03-12 16:30:00 in UTC+8.\n3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in that time window, compute: total points in window, count of anomaly points where value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5, earliest anomaly timestamp in the window (if any), max(value) and min(value) within the window, and the global_p95 and global_p5. \n4) Return a table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) sorted by anomaly count descending; include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_window, min_value_window, global_p95, global_p5. If anomaly_count is zero for all, return the top 20 by max_value_window desc instead. Keep outputs compact (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global p95/p5 for each component-KPI and then flagged anomaly points in the incident window (2021-03-12 16:00–16:30). The compact top20 table shows many (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs where every point in the 31-sample window was marked anomalous because the series values are constant and equal to the global thresholds (global_p95 == global_p5), which produces many false-positive anomaly flags. These constant-series anomalies are not informative for locating real faults. To find meaningful faults we must exclude constant series and focus on component-KPIs that actually vary in the window (max_value_window != min_value_window) and have anomaly points. From there we'll have a smaller set of candidates to inspect with traces and logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the existing kernel variable top20_results, filter rows where max_value_window != min_value_window AND anomaly_count > 0 (non-constant series with anomalies). Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc, including columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_window, min_value_window, global_p95, global_p5. Also return: (1) the distinct cmdb_id values present in this filtered set and their counts, (2) the earliest anomaly timestamp per cmdb_id (one row per cmdb_id). If the filtered set is empty, instead return the top 20 rows from top20_results with anomaly_count>0 sorted by (max_value_window - min_value_window) desc."
}

{
    "analysis": "We filtered metric anomalies to non-constant series and found only two component-KPI candidates with non-constant values flagged as anomalous during 2021-03-12 16:00–16:30 (UTC+8): IG01 (JVM-Memory_7778: NoHeapMemoryUsed) and IG02 (an OSLinux process metric related to zabbix agentd). For both rows every sample in the 31-point window was flagged anomalous and the earliest anomaly timestamp is 2021-03-12 16:00:00+08:00. These two component-level candidates are plausible root-cause candidates but metric anomalies alone are insufficient to decide the exact root cause and reason. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is trace analysis to determine which (if any) service in the call chain is the downstream faulty component and to confirm propagation patterns. Therefore we should inspect traces for IG01 and IG02 in the incident window to see if trace-level KPIs (e.g., latency, error counts) show anomalies and to identify which service calls are impacted.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, filter records to the time window March 12, 2021 16:00:00 to 2021-03-12 16:30:00 (UTC+8) and to cmdb_id values IG01 and IG02. For each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: count of points in window, earliest timestamp, latest timestamp, mean(value), max(value), and p95(value). Return a compact table sorted by count desc limited to top 20 rows. Also return a short list of distinct cmdb_id values found and the distinct trace_name values with their counts (limit the trace_name list to top 50 by count). Keep outputs compact (no full raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis for IG01 and IG02 (2021-03-12 16:00–16:30 UTC+8) shows elevated latency metrics: trace.self.duration_p95 and trace.to_Tomcat*.duration_p95 are high (p95 values up to ~9–10s, means much lower), and row_count metrics indicate normal traffic volume. Metric analysis earlier produced two non-constant anomalous component-KPI series: IG01:JVM-Memory_7778_JVM_Memory_NoHeapMemoryUsed and IG02:OSLinux-OSLinux_PROCESS_zabbix-..._PROCP (zabbix agentd related). Both had earliest anomaly at 2021-03-12 16:00:00+08:00 and every point in the window was flagged, but many other metric series were constant and created false-positive flags. At this stage we have two candidate faulty components (IG01 and IG02) whose traces exhibit high tail latency beginning at 16:00+08:00. To determine the exact root cause reason for each candidate, we must inspect relevant metric KPI categories (CPU, memory, network, disk, JVM) for IG01 and IG02 and search logs (log.csv and error_logs.csv) in the same window for corroborating error messages or events (e.g., OOM, GC spikes, network errors, disk errors).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, filter rows where cmdb_id is IG01 or IG02. For these rows, compute the distinct kpi_name values and their sample counts across the full available series (do NOT filter by time for threshold calculation). Return a compact table of the top 50 kpi_name entries sorted by count descending, including columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count. Also return a short list (per cmdb_id) of any kpi_name that contain the substrings: 'CPU', 'MEMORY', 'Memory', 'JVM', 'Heap', 'Network', 'NET', 'DISK', 'IO', 'OOM', 'gc', or 'thread' (case-insensitive) to help select resource-relevant KPIs for deeper analysis. Keep outputs bounded and do not return raw time series."
}

